---
description: Prefer declarative array transforms over imperative loops with mutable accumulators
globs: "**/*.{ts,tsx}"
alwaysApply: true
---

# Prefer Functional Style

Use `.filter()`, `.map()`, `.reduce()`, `.flatMap()` over `for` loops that push into mutable arrays. All intermediate variables should be `const`.

## What to avoid

```typescript
// ❌ Mutable accumulator + for loop
const results: Item[] = []
for (let i = 0; i < items.length; i++) {
  if (items[i].active) {
    results.push(transform(items[i]))
  }
}
```

## What to write instead

```typescript
// ✅ Declarative pipeline
const results = items
  .filter((item) => item.active)
  .map(transform)
```

## Index-aware filtering

When you need the original index alongside filtered items, use `.map()` to pair values with indices first:

```typescript
// ✅ Preserves original indices without mutation
const eligible = items
  .map((item, i) => ({ item, i }))
  .filter(({ item }) => item.active)

// Turn results into a lookup for O(1) application
const updateByIdx = new Map(
  eligible.map(({ i }, j) => [i, suggestions[j]] as const),
)

const updated = items.map((item, i) => {
  const patch = updateByIdx.get(i)
  return patch ? { ...item, ...patch } : item
})
```

## Exceptions

- Performance-critical hot paths where allocation matters (profiled, not assumed)
- Early-exit logic that `.find()` or `.some()` can't express
